column28:
*Background*

*Background:*
* We have a scrappy fixture that Jon's team made
* We need to make a more robust production ready fixture that is automated - a solution that can help us test 75,000 units next year
* What are the requirements that they are looking for
** Connectors or pogo pins? 
G1 is in Arena and we have part numbers on it
*Requirements:*
# Programming MCU​
* Via pogo pins - no connector for this
* We need the touch points 
* Standard J-tag emulator 
* Do this at PCBA functional only - Not at EOL
# Voltages monitoring and recording​ 
* We can do this using veri volts 
* Does not make sense to use a weco for this setup —> too expensive ($100k)  and > 6 months lead time
* EOL (both)
# Calibration​ 
* Monitor the voltages and currents using veri volts
* All the data will be recorded
* Do this at PCBA functional only - Not at EOL
# Efficiency sweep​
* Monitor the voltages and currents using veri volts
* All the data will be recorded
* Do this at PCBA functional only - Not at EOL
# Power measurement must be done with below 0.05% accuracy. Appropriate devices must be used.​
* Targeting a 1.0 meter class - At nominal ratings we will guarantee 1% error
* Monitor the voltages and currents using veri volts
* All the data will be recorded
* EOL (both)
# IR temperature measurements.​ *_This will not be included in our design_*
* This might be something that is required for design validation rather than M-test EOL
* We don’t generally do IR temperature measurements on EOL 
* We can log all the thermistor temperatures that are on the PCBA at both
# Galvanically isolated – must​
* Agreed —> All measurements will be galvanically isolated
* EOL (both)
# UART interface to MCU​ - PCBA functional tester
* Via pogo pins - no connector for this
* We need the touch points 
* Standard J-tag emulator 
* Do this at PCBA functional only - Not at EOL
# Sub minute operation – test speed must be optimized to finish within a minute, including 2 programming.
* What is driving this sub minute request?
* Calibration will take 2 minutes at least 
* Our current test on R2 takes around 20 minutes —> This will be similar initially
* Quick turn it will be about 20 minutes —> Optimization and scaling will take more time
* After lots of optimization work we can likely get it down to ~5 minutes —> This would require significant engineering effort 
* EOL (both)
*Mechanical:*
* 4 weeks from design lock (whenever the board is locked) - this can happen in parallel with electrical 
* First rev will be manual. We won’t need to deal with plugging in harnesses, etc. 
* 6 weeks for an automated solution 
*Next Steps:*
Get CAD for lastest version.
Mechanical Concept Review
Timeline review. Define due dates.
Create RFQ Package for Fixture
*Action Item:*
We need the design spec
We need the spec document
Need to have someone dedicated to Micro inverter 
Can we have a design review on the PWR Micro Fixture?  @Jon Thomas
What is going on with PWR Micro from a timeline standpoint? —> What are the need dates? - @Jan Sudra
We need another kickoff after we get the test spec and design spec from Jenia --> We should be getting those tomorrow - @Jan Sudra

*Timeline*

Timeline: November 15th is the deadline for testers to be prepared, allowing approximately 8 weeks for preparation.
Specifically, we will need 2x PCBA Fixtures (1 for Production, 1 for Compliance) and 1x EOL Fixture. The EOL Fixture should include side connectors, while the PCBA Fixture should have side access. Manual placement and clamping for PCBA are acceptable as long as the process takes approximately 10 seconds or less.
For the NPI 1 Build, we anticipate producing 1,000 units from November to February.
In July, production will commence with an initial volume of 30,000 units, continuing throughout the remainder of the year.
To meet the project requirements, we aim to design and construct 2 PCBA fixtures and 1 EOL fixture by November 8th.
Design and Build 2 PCBA fixture and 1 EOL fixture by 11/8
Ensure fixtures have side connectors for EOL and side access for PCBA
Address the need for fixtures: 2x PCBA (1 for Production, 1 for Compliance) and 1x EOL

column1: Fix bug in scripts that builds the UDS/datastore files for the devices
column28:
To prevent duplicate signals in datastore files, the python scripts were previously written for each device to filter the signals with 2 instances *(one for read_only = True, and the other for read_only = False)* by only including signals where *read_only = False*. This meant signals with only one instance where *read_only = True* were missed and not listed in the generated datastore files. This might explain the issues we’ve encountered when attempting to write via UDS to the BMU.

I have now improved this code to create the list to contain entries where if "read_only is not set to True" for signals that have other instances where "read_only is set to True" to filter out the duplicates, and also save the entries with only one instance where "read_only is set to True”.

06/Sep/24 10:45 AM;60957172a56f2f006f65f1e9;I verified this bug was addressed with an online text file comparator and observed a lot of signals with only one instance where *read_only = True,* which were previously missing are now included in the newly generated data store files. 

Below is a screenshot of the file comparator showing before and after the script was fixed.

column1: Unblock voltron 8822 PXIe
column28:
Slack conversation: [https://neurio.slack.com/archives/C05T1U2BUP5/p1725472214963159|https://neurio.slack.com/archives/C05T1U2BUP5/p1725472214963159|smart-link] 

5.19.0-50-generic Kernel version currently installed on PXI; diwngrading to this version removed the graphics and network driver son the PXI so there is no internet access to download and install NI and other useful packages.  

Proposed solution from Erich and Zeren: Upgrade kernel version to 6.0 [Ubuntu – Details of package linux-image-6.0.0-1021-oem in jammy|https://packages.ubuntu.com/jammy/linux-image-6.0.0-1021-oem]

Useful links:

[PXI Configuration - Core Test Engineering Technology - Confluence (atlassian.net)|https://generacet.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/CTET/pages/257197523/PXI+Configuration#Downgrade-the-Kernel-version]

[software uninstall - How to easily remove old kernels in Ubuntu 20.04 LTS? - Ask Ubuntu|https://askubuntu.com/questions/1253347/how-to-easily-remove-old-kernels-in-ubuntu-20-04-lts]
column174:
05/Sep/24 11:55 AM;60957172a56f2f006f65f1e9;How to create bootable USB disk on Windows: [Installation/FromUSBStick - Community Help Wiki (ubuntu.com)|https://help.ubuntu.com/community/Installation/FromUSBStick]

 [Create a bootable USB stick with Rufus on Windows | Ubuntu|https://ubuntu.com/tutorials/create-a-usb-stick-on-windows#2-requirements]

How to install Ubuntu Desktop from bootable USB disk: [Install Ubuntu desktop | Ubuntu|https://ubuntu.com/tutorials/install-ubuntu-desktop]
column175:
05/Sep/24 12:13 PM;60957172a56f2f006f65f1e9;I was unable to update to 6.0.0-1021 version because there were a lot of dependencies that were missing to complete the installation locally, and there was no internet connection, so Erich suggested booting via a live image of Ubuntu 22.04. 

I started this process, but stopped because I got to the installer menu and would have wiped the PXIe. 

*Current Resolution:*
I restarted the 8822 PXIe and during boot up, I pressed F10 to see the boot menu.
I randomly selected the 5.19.0-1030-lowlatency to verify if another Linux image had the graphics and network drivers installed; so that I could update the kernel version on the PXIe to 6.0.0-1021. I observed the graphics and some of the network drivers were installed on this version, but I noticed the WiFi and bluetooth (wireless connectivity) drivers were missing on this one. (This doesn’t block us; we will rely on LAN)

!image-20240905-191010.png|width=519,height=261,alt="image-20240905-191010.png"!

During the CTET SW sprint, I brought this up and we discussed to remain on this kernel version {color:#ff991f}(5.19.0-1030-lowlatency) {color}until this issue has been understood and addressed.

I then updated the grub to ensure the system always powers up with the 5.19.0-1030-lowlatency image by issuing the following via the terminal:

{noformat}# change the grub configuration
sudo vim /etc/default/grub

# make this change in the file
from: GRUB_DEFAULT=0
to: GRUB_DEFAULT="Advanced options for Ubuntu>Ubuntu, with Linux 5.19.0-1030-lowlatency"

# update grub
sudo update-grub

# reboot
sudo reboot

# verify Linux image after reboot
uname -r{noformat}
column176:
05/Sep/24 12:15 PM;60957172a56f2f006f65f1e9;*Uninstall and re-install NI drivers:*

{noformat}sudo apt purge ni-pxiplatformservices -y
sudo apt autoremove
sudo apt autoclean
sudo apt install ni-pxiplatformservices -y
sudo apt install ni-daqmx -y
sudo dkms autoinstall
sudo reboot{noformat}

After the restart, I verified the modules were visible in the configuration utility app, and I ran test.go which was successful.
column177: 05/Sep/24 1:53 PM;60957172a56f2f006f65f1e9;{{sudo apt install linux-modules-extra-5.19.0-50-generic}}  was issued to install those missing drivers and started the system with the 5.19.0-50-generic image. This installed the graphic driver and permitted internet connectivity via LAN. Though, similarly to the -low latency version, the 5.19.0-50-generic does not have any wireless extensions. Per Erich, Zeren has a fix for that; some driver we need to download off GitHub, build, install.
